","Lackford, Suffolk, England":"Lackford, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gedding","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German:","habitational name from any of various places called Wedding or Weddingen.","variant of <b>Weddig</b>, a short form of   Wedekind  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wedekind","meanings":["North German: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>wid(u)</i> ‘wood, forest’ + <i>kind</i> ‘child’. The name became famous as that of a Duke of Lower Saxony who was an opponent of Charlemagne, and was consequently popular in northern Germany as a personal name in the Middle Ages."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Gedding was born in 1368, his father, John Gedding, was 43 and his mother, Bruce, was 42. He married Myrabel de Aspall in 1384, in Lackford, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"1368–":"1368–Surnud","1368–Male":"1368–Surnud","1370–1406":"1370–1406","1390–1469":"1390–1469","1400–1465":"1400–1465","1325–Male":"1325–Surnud","13